Session ID generated by mPulse and stored in a cookie by Boomerang.<br><br>The first five chunks are a UUID  while the last chunk is the base36 representation of the session start time based on the user's clock.

Session start time ([Unix epoch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_time)) based on the user's browser's clock.<br><br>This clock may not be in sync with the server clock  so only compare it with other browser timestamps.

The timestamp ([Unix epoch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_time)) of the current beacon based on the user's browser's clock.<br><br>It is not the timestamp of the latest beacon in the session.<br><br>To find out actual session duration  look at MAX(latest) - MIN(start) across all beacons grouped by Session ID.

The number of pages the user viewed in this session up to and including the current page  but not including any pages viewed after this page in the same session.<br><br>To find out actual Session Length in pages  look at MAX(pages) across all beacons grouped by Session ID.<br><br>If MAX(pages) == 1  then the session is considered a bounce.
The number of pages in the session for which we were unable to calculate a load time.<br><br>We need this to get a closer estimate of the actual average load time of all pages in the session.
The sum of load times (in milliseconds) of all pages within the session where we calculated load time.<br><br>The average load time of a session is MAX(totalLoadTime) / (MAX(pages) - MAX(oboPages)).
This field specifies if the beacon was part of the unload event of the page or not.<br><br>Unload beacons give us a better idea of how long a session actually lasted.

Examples: Chrome Firefox IE Safari Mobile Safari
